  "prompt": "What parts should I upgrade on my PC?",
  "response": "To give you the best advice on what parts to upgrade on your PC, I need some more information!  Think of me as your PC upgrade consultant.  Tell me about:\n\n**1. Your Current PC Specifications:**\n\n*   **CPU (Processor):**  Make and model (e.g., Intel Core i5-8400, AMD Ryzen 5 3600).\n*   **Motherboard:**  Make and model (e.g., ASUS ROG Strix B450-F Gaming).  If you don't know this precisely, the chipset is helpful (e.g., B450, Z390, X570). You can find this by running `msinfo32` in Windows Search.\n*   **RAM:**  Amount (e.g., 16GB) and speed (e.g., 3200MHz) - also, how many sticks?  (e.g., 2x8GB).  You can find this in Task Manager (Performance tab -> Memory).\n*   **Graphics Card (GPU):**  Make and model (e.g., NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060, AMD Radeon RX 6700 XT).\n*   **Storage:**\n    *   **Primary Drive (where your operating system is installed):**  Type (SSD or HDD) and capacity (e.g., 500GB NVMe SSD).  Is it SATA or NVMe (M.2)?\n    *   **Secondary Drives:**  Type and capacity (e.g., 1TB HDD, 2TB SATA SSD).\n*   **Power Supply (PSU):**  Wattage (e.g., 650W) and ideally, efficiency rating (e.g., 80+ Gold).  This is usually printed on the PSU itself.  **Important:** Upgrading certain components (like the GPU) often requires a more powerful PSU.\n*   **Case:**  Knowing the case can help determine what size components you can fit (e.g., ATX Mid-Tower).\n*   **Monitor:** Resolution and refresh rate (e.g., 1920x1080 @ 144Hz, 2560x1440 @ 60Hz, 3840x2160 @ 144Hz). This affects what upgrades will be most noticeable.\n\n**2. What You Use Your PC For:**\n\n*   **Gaming:**  What games do you play, and at what settings/resolution/framerate are you aiming for?  (e.g., \"I want to play Cyberpunk 2077 at 1440p, high settings, 60+ FPS,\" or \"I mostly play eSports titles like Valorant and want high refresh rates\").\n*   **Productivity:**  Video editing, photo editing, graphic design, programming, general office work?  Which software do you use (e.g., Adobe Premiere Pro, Photoshop, AutoCAD, Visual Studio)?\n*   **Streaming:**  Do you stream on Twitch/YouTube?\n*   **General Use:**  Web browsing, watching videos, etc.\n\n**3. Your Budget:**\n\n*   What's the maximum amount you're willing to spend on upgrades?  Knowing your budget is crucial to recommending realistic options.\n*   Are you willing to buy used parts?  This can often get you more performance for your money.\n\n**4. What Problems Are You Trying to Solve?**\n\n*   **Slow performance?**  Where are you noticing the slowness (e.g., long loading times, lag in games, slow startup)?\n*   **Can't run certain games at desired settings?**\n*   **Need more storage space?**\n*   **Want to improve overall responsiveness?**\n*   **Upgrading for future-proofing?**  (Note: Future-proofing is difficult, but we can aim for longevity).\n\n**Example of a Good Response (to give you an idea):**\n\n\"Okay, here's my setup:\n\n*   **CPU:** Intel Core i5-8400\n*   **Motherboard:** ASUS Prime B360M-A\n*   **RAM:** 16GB (2x8GB) DDR4 2400MHz\n*   **GPU:** NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1060 6GB\n*   **Storage:** 256GB SATA SSD (boot drive), 1TB HDD\n*   **PSU:** 550W 80+ Bronze\n*   **Case:**  Standard Mid-Tower ATX\n*   **Monitor:** 1920x1080 @ 60Hz\n\nI mainly use my PC for gaming. I play games like Apex Legends, Fortnite, and some newer AAA titles like Cyberpunk 2077. I'd like to be able to play newer games at 1080p with higher settings and maintain a stable 60 FPS.  I'm also starting to do some light video editing in DaVinci Resolve. My budget is around $500-$700. I'm open to buying used parts if it makes sense.  The biggest problem is that I'm getting low frame rates in newer games, and video editing feels slow.\"\n\n**Once I have this information, I can give you much more specific and helpful recommendations!**\n",
